- All user story acceptance criteria in this project **must STRICTLY** be written in **Gherkin format**.

##Story **summary/title** 

prefix with feature short name in brackets (e.g. `[Caching] Short description`). Followed by a story title/summary (max 10 word)

```story narrative
  *As a* [role]
  *I want* [goal]
  *So that* [benefit]
```

## **Gherkin Acceptance Criteria** (**Do not** print this in user story)

|| Scenario || Given || When || Then ||
| *[Scenario name]* | [precondition] | [action] | [observable outcome] |

*(Repeat the table row for each acceptance criterion. For `And` / `But`, add lines inside the same **Given**, **When**, or **Then** cell, each on a new line and prefixed with **And** or **But**, as appropriate.)*

## Non-functional requirements (NFRs)
- **Strictly When applicable**, add NFRs explicitly. Do not force NFRs onto every story; 
- add them where they matter (e.g. performance, security, accessibility, scale).
- NFRs can be written as:
  - Gherkin-style scenarios (e.g. `Scenario: Response time under load` with Given/When/Then), or
  - Short, testable statements (e.g. "Page must meet WCAG 2.1 AA" or "P95 latency < 200ms").
- Prefer one NFR section or scenario per concern so they are traceable.

## Additional Information
- Ensure each story in Jira contains **Maps to:** each requirement ID (e.g. REQ-AUTH-01) in the description field. REQ-AUTH-01 hyperlinks to the requirement confluence page where requirements are listed. 

## Jira field mapping & defaults
When publishing stories to Jira, see `.cursor/defaults.md` (section "Jira Story Defaults") for field mapping and default values.
